# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-urban-art-graffiti-vandalism
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Urban art is just graffiti or vandalism."@en ;
  curric:correction """Urban art includes many creative and meaningful responses to city life - from
  murals and installations to Fine Art inspired by architecture. It can be legal,
  expressive, and community-based."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085063Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-digital-tools-necessary-street-art
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Digital tools are not necessary for street art; real street art has to be done
  with spray paint on walls."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While spray paint is common in street art, digital tools are increasingly
  used in the design and creation process. Digital art allows artists to experiment, refine,
  and plan their murals before transferring them to large-scale physical surfaces."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086645Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-types-smile-indicate-happiness-person
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All types of smile indicate happiness in a person."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are many nuances in smiles, such as a polite smile versus a genuine
  smile, which can convey different feelings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087488Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-idea-drawn-finished
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Once an idea has been drawn, it is finished."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists often revisit and refine their ideas. A first sketch is just the
  starting point - you can improve your work by trying different layouts, materials, and
  colour choices."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.088932Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-characters-need-look-good-dont
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Characters just need to look good, they don’t need to mean anything."@en ;
  curric:correction """Great character design includes meaning with symbols and design choices
  conveying personality and mood."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089069Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-protests-loud-dangerous
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All protests are loud and dangerous."@en ;
  curric:correction "Protest can be peaceful and placards can be a safe way to share ideas."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089978Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-portrait-look-real-neat-show
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A portrait has to look real or neat to show who someone is."@en ;
  curric:correction """Portraits can show feeling, memory, or mood without looking realistic.
  Artists use colour, texture and shape to tell a story about the person."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090441Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-environment-anywhere-important-clues-story
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The environment can be anywhere; the most important clues for a story are from
  the characters and objects."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The setting is an important device for communicating a story. It shows where
  the story happens and adds clues about mood, time, or place."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090796Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-graffiti-letters-supposed-messy-hard
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Graffiti letters are always supposed to be messy or hard to read."@en ;
  curric:correction """While some graffiti can be abstract or complex, many styles focus on
  legibility and clarity, especially in tags and block letters. Graffiti artists often
  balance style with readability, making their work both creative and accessible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091017Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-object-used-doesnt-mean-anything
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any object can be used as it doesn’t have to mean anything."@en ;
  curric:correction """Objects can be used to help tell stories and add depth and meaning through
  what they symbolise."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-street-art-graffiti-vandalism-real
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Street art is just graffiti and vandalism, not real art."@en ;
  curric:correction """While some street art is made without permission, many street artists
  communicate meaningful social or political messages. Street art is a legitimate and
  powerful art form that challenges societal norms and promotes dialogue."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091194Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-faces-symmetrical-proportions-fit-set
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Faces are symmetrical and all proportions should fit to set guidelines."@en ;
  curric:correction """Most faces are asymmetrical with different proportions. Guidelines for
  drawing faces give only a rough estimation of where features might be placed, and will
  differ for each person, as we are all unique."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091791Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-colouring-everything-neatly-makes-finished
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Colouring everything in neatly makes a finished artwork."@en ;
  curric:correction """Finishing an artwork isn’t just about colouring - it’s about choosing colours
  and adding details that help tell the story more clearly and powerfully."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091976Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-need-use-leaves
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that they will need to always use leaves when creating a
  frottage. Pupils may think frottage involves drawing objects such as leaves."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Frottage involves rubbing over textures, not drawing them. It captures the
  texture of surfaces rather than depicting them with lines. While leaves are commonly used,
  frottage can be done with various textured objects like coins or wood."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092846Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-urban-design-buildings-roads
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Urban design is only about buildings and roads."@en ;
  curric:correction """Urban design includes public spaces, such as parks, playgrounds, and
  recreational areas. Urban design is about how people use and experience space, not just
  what gets built."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092942Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-final-outcome-look-identical-original
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A final outcome must look identical to the original plan."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists adapt ideas during making. Their plan is a starting point - not a
  rule. Changing materials or layout during creation is part of the artistic process."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092949Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-symbol-one-meaning-everyone
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A symbol has only one meaning for everyone."@en ;
  curric:correction """Symbols can mean different things in different cultures or to different
  people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092955Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-recycled-materials-rubbish-art-made
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Recycled materials are rubbish, and art made from them is not important."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists turn everyday scraps into powerful pieces. Using waste shows we care
  for the planet and value every material, big or small."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pop-art-cartoon-drawing-copying
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pop Art is just cartoon drawing or copying famous things."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pop Art uses familiar imagery to comment on culture, not just to copy it.
  Artists chose their subjects carefully to reflect society’s values and consumer habits."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093320Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-wild-animals-dont-belong-cities
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Wild animals don’t belong in cities and can’t survive there."@en ;
  curric:correction """While some wild animals struggle in cities, others adapt well if we design
  spaces with them in mind. Urban environments can become important habitats with thoughtful
  planning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094610Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-urban-design-solely-constructing-buildings
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Urban design is solely about constructing buildings.​"@en ;
  curric:correction """Urban design encompasses the planning of entire city environments, including
  streets, public spaces, transportation systems and the relationships between different
  urban elements.​"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.095991Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-researching-means-copying-images-exactly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Researching means copying images exactly into your final artwork."@en ;
  curric:correction """Research is about gathering inspiration and developing ideas, not copying.
  Artists reinterpret and combine sources in creative and personal ways."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.095997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sketchbooks-finished-drawings
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sketchbooks are for finished drawings only."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sketchbooks are working spaces. They’re for exploring, not perfecting.
  Artists use them to test, plan and reflect, not to make polished work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.096519Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-graffiti-art-using-spray-paint
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Graffiti art is only about using spray paint on walls."@en ;
  curric:correction """Graffiti can be done using many mediums, including digital media, and digital
  tools allow us to explore and refine our designs without needing physical walls. Graffiti
  is about expression, regardless of the medium."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.096524Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sustainable-transport-electric-vehicles
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sustainable transport is just about electric vehicles."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sustainability includes more than just power sources - it also involves
  materials, passenger capacity, energy use, and reducing pollution across a whole system."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.096880Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-patterns-medieval-paintings-decoration
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Patterns in medieval paintings were just decoration."@en ;
  curric:correction """Patterns actually had symbolic and spiritual meanings, helping people
  understand religious ideas when most couldn’t read."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.096886Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-street-art-spontaneous-cant-planned
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Street art has to be spontaneous and can't be planned or created
  digitally."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While street art often has a spontaneous nature, digital tools allow artists
  to plan and refine their designs before sharing them publicly. Digital art can provide
  more control and flexibility, allowing for thoughtful and intentional compositions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097198Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-my-sculpture-needs-show-action
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "My sculpture needs to show action or be realistic."@en ;
  curric:correction """Our sculpture can be still, soft, or bulky. It doesn't need to move or look
  like a real person to hold meaning. Wrapping and shaping can show something inside you, a
  memory, a feeling or a story, without using words."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097395Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pop-art-looks-same-its
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Pop Art looks the same - it’s just bold colours and celebrities."@en ;
  curric:correction """Each Pop artist had a unique message and approach. Some explored consumerism,
  others made emotional or political statements."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098047Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-art-last-forever
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that art has to last forever to be important or valuable."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that art can be ephemeral - meaning it lasts only a short time
  - and still be very important. Just like nature’s changes, temporary art helps us notice
  beauty, tell stories, and understand ideas about growth and resilience."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098082Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-create-expressive-letterform-neat-handwriting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "To create an expressive letterform you must have neat handwriting skills."@en ;
  curric:correction """Expressive letterforms use drawing and designing skills to convey emotions
  and ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098445Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-parts-sculpture-detailed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that all parts of the sculpture must be detailed."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that it’s better to focus on key features like the face,
  wings, or texture, rather than decorating every part. This keeps your design clear and
  makes your creature stand out."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.099361Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stitches-used-join-materials-together
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Stitches are just used to join materials together."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that, while stitches can be used to join materials together,
  they are also used in a skilled and decorative way through embroidery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.099368Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-including-personal-materials-artwork-effect
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Including personal materials in artwork has no effect on how emotional or
  powerful the art feels."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists might use personal materials to tell a story,
  share a memory, or express emotions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.099502Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-leaves-uniform-shape
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that leaves are uniform in shape, when in fact rainforest
  leaves vary greatly in shape and size."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Highlight the diversity of plant forms and individuality of shape in the
  lesson."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101250Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-use-same-brush-size
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils might use the same brush size for the entire painting."@en ;
  curric:correction """Demonstrate how larger brushes are best for covering big areas like the
  background, while smaller brushes are ideal for details like leaves, veins, or animal
  features. Provide examples of how different brush sizes create varied textures and
  effects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-typographic-designs-minimal-because-otherwise
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Typographic designs should be minimal because otherwise they are hard to read
  and do not communicate a clear message."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Typography enhances the clarity of a design, making text easier to read by
  arranging elements with a visual hierarchy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101540Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-shapes-use-need
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think the shapes they use need to be perfect or uniform when
  sketching."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children of the difference between organic and geometric shapes.
  Organic shapes do not need to be uniform or perfect."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-emotions-conveyed-words-physical-gestures
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Emotions are only conveyed through words and physical gestures."@en ;
  curric:correction """Facial expressions are a universal way to communicate emotions, even without
  words."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.102479Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adding-many-decorations-make-mask
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Adding too many decorations will make the mask too busy or overwhelming."@en ;
  curric:correction """It’s important to find balance in the mask’s design. Decoration can enhance
  the mask and highlight specific areas, such as the eyes or mouth, without overcrowding the
  mask’s overall look. Less can be more in some areas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.102889Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stitching-onto-paper-exactly-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Stitching onto paper is exactly the same as stitching onto fabric."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that stitching on paper requires a few things to be mindful
  of, including preparing holes in your paper and not pulling your thread too tightly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.102996Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-monoprinting-making-copy-creativity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Monoprinting is only about making a copy, not about creativity."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that monoprinting is a form of artistic expression. Artists
  can use monoprinting to create unique, creative works where textures, colours and styles
  can vary greatly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.103340Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-letters-used-reading
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Letters are only used for reading"@en ;
  curric:correction "Letters can be used to make interesting and beautiful designs"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.103624Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-need-plan-self-portrait-concrete
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You do not need to plan a self-portrait concrete poem. You should just start
  by writing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that planning some descriptive words or phrases can help to
  ensure their emotions or message are communicated effectively in their concrete poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.103837Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lines-building-go-straight-sideways
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All the lines in a building should go straight up and sideways."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some lines go towards a vanishing point to show how things look smaller as
  they get further away. That’s how we create perspective."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104394Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-needle-felting-tools-easy-use
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Needle felting tools are easy to use without considering safety."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that felting needles are extremely sharp. They should be used
  with a high consideration of safety, particularly ensuring fingers and eyes are protected."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104403Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-maquette-final-version
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils could think the maquette is the final version of their sculpture,
  rather than a starting point for refining and improving their design."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that a maquette is a guide for their sculpture, not a final
  blueprint. Emphasise that it's okay to make changes as they work to improve stability and
  functionality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104428Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-use-one-material-create
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists can only use one material to create tone in an artwork."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists can use a range of materials within one artwork
  to show tone. This is called a mixed-media artwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104434Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-material-used-body
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think any material can be used for any body part, like using
  lightweight or flexible materials for the base instead of sturdy ones."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show examples of sculptures with a sturdy base versus those with a weak base,
  using different materials (e.g., cardboard vs tissue paper)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104440Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-shapes-look-abstract-seems-like
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "If the shapes look abstract, it seems like they don’t mean anything."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists often use abstract shapes and textures to suggest hidden meaning or
  feeling. Symbols and patterns can carry personal or spiritual meaning - and sometimes,
  part of the power is in the mystery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-strong-emotions-seen-facial-expressions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only strong emotions can be seen as facial expressions."@en ;
  curric:correction """Facial expressions can sometimes be subtle or mixed, making them challenging
  to identify accurately."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104497Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-buildings-look-same-because-follow
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All buildings look the same because they follow similar rules."@en ;
  curric:correction """While buildings need to be safe and follow certain rules, architects use
  creativity to make them unique."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104959Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-group-critiques-suggest-ways
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Artists have group critiques to just suggest ways to make an artwork
  better."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Group critiques can be useful for an artist to get new ideas or suggestions,
  but are also useful for other artists to hear the reasons behind the artist's choices."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105368Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cake-design-realistic-good
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A cake design must be realistic to be good."@en ;
  curric:correction """While realism can help in some design projects, creative and exaggerated
  designs can make cakes visually exciting and unique."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105491Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-photographic-images-reflect-reality
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Photographic images always reflect reality."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that photographic images can be digitally manipulated using a
  computer or digital software, they do not always reflect reality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105678Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-good-cake-inspired-sculpture-look
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A good cake-inspired sculpture must look realistic."@en ;
  curric:correction """Cake-inspired sculptures can be creative, experiment with textures, colours
  and other ideas, not just realistic depictions. Great art can be a combination of
  interpretation and imagination."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-templates-need-pinned-fabric
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Templates do not need to be pinned to fabric."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that pinning before cutting allows you to adjust the
  placement of your templates."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105822Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-identity-means-one-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Identity means one thing about you."@en ;
  curric:correction """Identity is made of many parts - culture, hobbies, family, beliefs - and a
  collage can mix images to show all those layers of who you are."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105871Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-traditionally-cultures-use-paintbrushes-paint
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Traditionally, all cultures use paintbrushes to paint."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that although paintbrushes are a popular artistic tool, they
  are not traditional for every community or culture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105890Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rolling-pin-rest-guide-sticks
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The rolling pin does not have to rest on the guide sticks to ensure an even
  consistency of clay."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that the rolling pin should rest on both of the guide
  sticks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.106317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-storyboards-need-perfect
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that storyboards need to be perfect and spend more time on
  the details of the drawing as opposed to thinking about the sequence of events of their
  animation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that storyboards are rough sketches that help plan the
  sequence of the animation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.106906Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-collages-three-dimensional
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Collages are always three-dimensional."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that collages can be three-dimensional, but can also be made
  on a flat surface."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.107206Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-take-inspiration-same-features
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists can only take inspiration from the same features of a landmark."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists can look at the same landmark, but choose to
  take inspiration from different features. Finding different things inspiring is an
  important part of being an artist."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.107337Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-choose-recycled-materials-randomly-without
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You can choose recycled materials randomly without considering your robot's
  purpose or the material's properties."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to focus on the robot's main purpose first, like its key
  features (e.g. arms for cleaning). Once those are in place, they can add extra details.
  Remind them to refer to their maquettes to stay focused."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.107981Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-charcoal-messy-control-mistakes-cant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Charcoal is too messy to control, and mistakes can’t be fixed."@en ;
  curric:correction """Charcoal is a flexible material. Smudging can be used to soften mistakes or
  use a rubber to refine shapes and add highlights."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108112Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-shading-means-colouring-darker
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Shading just means colouring in darker."@en ;
  curric:correction """Tonal shading uses a range of light to dark tones to show how light hits
  different surfaces."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108407Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-long-model-shown-doesnt-need
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "As long as a model is shown, it doesn't need to be explained."@en ;
  curric:correction """It’s important to explain your ideas clearly - your model shows the design,
  but your words help others understand why and how you made it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108917Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-easier-sketch-outline-without-first
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "It is easier to sketch an outline without first using shapes."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that if we use shapes to plan our drawing, it becomes much
  easier to achive the correct position and proportions with our outline."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109192Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-group-work-means-one-small
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Group work means I only do one small part and don’t need to help with the
  rest."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While roles may be shared, everyone in the group should contribute ideas and
  help make decisions together to ensure the final design feels like a team effort."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109526Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-need-observe-reality-make
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists need to observe from reality to make art."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that art can be an observation, but it can also be taking an
  idea we have in our heads and making it into an artwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109578Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-responding-subject-making-copy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Responding to a subject is making  a copy of it."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that responding to an artwork means reacting to it, rather
  than just reproducing it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109586Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-paintbrush-used-one-effect
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A paintbrush can only be used for one effect."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that a paintbrush can be used to create many different
  effects, such as dry-brush and wet on wet."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109691Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-stop-motion-animation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that stop motion animation is the same as a video recording.
  They may think that you need expensive equipment to create stop motion animations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that stop motion animation is created by taking individual
  still images. A video recording captures continuous motion. It can be created using simple
  and readily available devices."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109697Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-clay-cannot-worked-unless-wet
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Clay cannot be worked with unless it is very wet."@en ;
  curric:correction """Clay can be worked with when it is leather hard. This means it has dried out
  slightly, so it can be stronger to work with."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109703Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-maquette-finished-sculpture-model-planning
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A maquette is a finished sculpture, not a model for planning a design."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that building a maquette is an opportunity to test different
  elements of their design, allowing them to identify areas for improvement. A maquette does
  not need to be perfect as its purpose is to resolve issues before the final design."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109850Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-paper-cut-printing-process-cannot
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A paper-cut printing process cannot be used to create multiple prints from the
  same templates."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists might choose this process as they can make
  multiple prints from the same templates."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109856Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-landmarks-human-made
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Landmarks are always human-made."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that some landmarks are made by humans but others are natural
  formations, such as cliffs, trees or waterfalls."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110512Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-arpilleras-generally-avoid-themes-related
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Arpilleras generally avoid themes related to daily life or social issues."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that arpilleras are typically appliquéd textile scenes,
  showing everyday life, rural culture, or times of conflict. Arpilleras are sometimes used
  as activist art, especially in the context of human rights or social justice."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111509Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-colours-neutral-evoke-emotion
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Colours are neutral and do not evoke emotion."@en ;
  curric:correction """Colours can evoke a wide range of different emotions. For example, blue might
  suggest calmness while red might indicate anger."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112083Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-content-text-conveys-essential-information
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The content of text conveys all essential information."@en ;
  curric:correction """Typograhy, typefaces, and letterform designs can change the emotion and
  message of written text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112442Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mask-shape-perfectly-symmetrical-look
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A mask shape must be perfectly symmetrical to look good."@en ;
  curric:correction """While symmetry is often used, asymmetry can also be used to create dynamic
  and interesting designs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-concrete-poems-drawings-decorated-words
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Concrete poems are drawings decorated with words."@en ;
  curric:correction """Concrete poems integrate text with a shape to convey meaning. They are not
  merely drawings decorated with words."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112609Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-abstract-art-copies-exactly-something
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Abstract art copies exactly what something looks like."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that abstract art is art that does not try to represent
  something realistically, but instead focuses on emotions, shapes and movements."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112892Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-cross-hatching-drawing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some children might think cross-hatching is just drawing straight lines to
  create shading."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show pupils different examples of cross-hatching and allow time to practise
  other shading techniques."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112898Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sculpture-glued-stuck-together-finished
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sculpture has to be glued or stuck together to be finished."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that some sculptures are temporary – artists sometimes build
  things that can fall, change or disappear."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113380Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-my-sculpture-look-like-real
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "My sculpture has to look like a real person to say something important."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that sculptures can be bold, simplified or abstract and still
  carry strong messages. Artists like Sokari Douglas Camp use pose, pattern and costume to
  express complex ideas about history, power and pride."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113391Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-even-coils-dont-stick-together
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Even if the coils don't stick together, the pot will still hold together once
  it dries or after it's fired."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Coils need to be properly joined using slip to ensure they don’t separate
  during the drying or firing process."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113904Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-look-same-landscape-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "When artists look at the same landscape, their artwork will look similar."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that sometimes artists will make artwork that looks similar,
  but this is not always the case. Artists can interpret their inspiration using their own,
  individual style."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-repeating-patterns-natural
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that all repeating patterns are natural patterns, even if
  they are man-made."""@en ;
  curric:correction """To help clarify, you could emphasise that natural patterns are found in
  nature. Nature walks can be a hands-on way to help students discover natural patterns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114099Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-3d-card-designs-require-glue
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All 3D card designs require glue or tape to stick pieces together."@en ;
  curric:correction """Techniques such as slotting can be used to create strong and effective 3D
  card structures, even without the use of glue."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114105Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-nature-cities-cant-go-together
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Nature and cities can’t go together."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that many cities already mix nature into their design - with
  green roofs, gardens, trees, and wildlife spaces. Cities can be sustainable and
  nature-friendly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114538Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-anything-found-outside
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think that anything found outside is natural, even if it is
  actually human-made. For example, bricks, fences, playground equipment, or painted
  surfaces."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that natural means it comes from nature and wasn’t made by
  people. Human-made means humans designed or built it, even if you find it outside."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114608Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-art-made-traditional-art-materials
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Art is only made from traditional art materials."@en ;
  curric:correction """Art can be made from almost anything, including plastic waste, as in the case
  of Mandy Barker."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115436Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-content-creator-promote-event-posters
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A content creator must always promote an event through posters and videos to
  be successful."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that while posters and videos are useful, an event can also
  be successfully promoted through spoken messages, social media, or written adverts. The
  key is to share clear and engaging information, not just the format used."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115517Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-games-aesthetic-need-consistent-throughout
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A game's aesthetic does not need to be consistent throughout the game."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that keeping the graphics, sounds, colours and feelings the
  same throughout the game helps players stay focused and understand the game better."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115528Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-rarely-use-their-work
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Artists rarely use their work to respond to conflict or explore its impact on
  people and society."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists have often responded to war and conflict by
  using their work to express the pain, fear, and devastation experienced by those affected."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115537Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-fashion-collection-assortment-clothes-accessories
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A fashion collection is an assortment of clothes and accessories with no
  common theme or coordinating colours."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that a fashion collection consists of clothes and accessories
  that share colours, fabrics, or themes designed to showcase the particular style of a
  fashion designer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115638Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-symbols-pictures-dont-really-mean
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Symbols are just pictures - they don’t really mean anything."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that symbols are pictures with power. People use them to show
  who they are, what they believe in, or what they want to change. On banners, every shape
  and colour can tell a story."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115959Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-clay-wet-stick-together-hold
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """If the clay is wet, it will stick together and hold without needing to apply
  slip."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Clay must be wet enough to join properly. Without slip, dry clay won't bond
  effectively, leading to cracks. The best way to stick together different pieces of clay is
  to score each side and use slip to ensure a secure connection."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117227Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-responding-image-means-making-exact
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Responding to an image means making an exact copy"@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that a response means taking an idea but changing it slightly
  to make it yours."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117835Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-single-thick-layer-modroc-create
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A single thick layer of modroc will create a strong sculpture."@en ;
  curric:correction """Modroc works best when thin layers are built up gradually. This allows the
  material to dry properly and allows the sculpture to become stronger."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117840Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-assemblage-sculptures-cannot-contain-drawn
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Assemblage sculptures cannot contain drawn and collaged elements."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that assemblage is a form of sculpture that includes everyday
  objects but can also be made from natural materials, manufactured items, photographs, text
  and drawings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119749Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artistic-choices-change-creative-process
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artistic choices never change during the creative process."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists often make creative adjustments as they work,
  changing their ideas, materials, or processes based on how the artwork is developing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119763Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-history-ended-long-ago-nothing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "History ended long ago; it has nothing to do with today."@en ;
  curric:correction """History still affects life now. By talking about past injustice, maybe
  through art, we learn how to build a fairer present"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.121004Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-festivals-global-events
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All festivals are global events."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that while some festivals are celebrated globally, such as
  New Year's Eve, other festivals are celebrated only in particular areas or countries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.122890Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sources-copied-exactly-create-good
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sources should be copied from exactly to create a good design."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sources are for inspiration, not replication. Great designs mix ideas from
  multiple sources and add personal creativity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123694Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-robots-one-job
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may assume robots have only one job, not understanding how versatile
  robots can be when designed for different tasks such as cleaning, farming, or saving
  resources."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that robots can have many different purposes! Show images of
  robots used in various ways, like cleaning oceans, planting trees, or sorting recyclables."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123700Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-reflecting-your-work-happens-finished
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Reflecting on your work only happens when you have finished making it."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that reflecting on the success of your work and areas that
  could be improved can happen both during and after the making of your work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-complementary-colours-located-next-other
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Complementary colours are located next to each other on the colour wheel."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that complementary colours are opposite each other on the
  colour wheel, not next to each other. This opposite placement is what creates their high
  contrast and visual vibrancy when paired."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123711Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-western-portraits-artworks-artists-represent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Western portraits are the artworks where artists represent stauts
  effectively."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many artefacts and artworks around the world and throughout history
  do this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123719Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-opinions-artwork-shared-words
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Opinions about an artwork can only be shared through words."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that we can share our opinions about an artwork with both a
  verbal and a visual response. It is another way of telling others what interests us most
  about an artwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124304Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-evaluation-reflection-takes-place-artwork
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Evaluation and reflection only takes place when the artwork is complete."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that reflecting upon your artwork can be useful at any stage of
  the creative process. It helps the artist recognise their successes and decide upon areas
  that could be improved and refined."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124369Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-assemblage-sculptures-carved-moulded
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Assemblage sculptures are carved or moulded."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that an assemblage sculpture is not usually carved or
  moulded, but parts are assembled using glue, tape, wire or thread."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124787Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-charcoal-colouring-outlines
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Charcoal is just for colouring or outlines."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that charcoal is a powerful tool for mood and space – it can
  create atmosphere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124807Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-model-looks-good-doesnt-matter
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "If the model looks good, it doesn’t matter if it does not stand properly."@en ;
  curric:correction """A successful architectural model is both visually creative and structurally
  sound. Aim to build with purpose to create stability."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.125551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-important-consider-identity-festival-creating
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is not important to consider the identity of the festival when creating
  your logo."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that graphic designers should consider the unique character
  of their festival when creating their logo, so they can visually represent the ethos of
  the event in their design."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.125656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-pressing-hard-makes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think pressing down hard makes the print clearer."@en ;
  curric:correction "Applying even pressure will result in a clearer print."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.127328Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-fabric-colour-palette-selected-precisely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The fabric colour palette selected should precisely match the colours present
  in the petri dish."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists might choose to take inspiration from a similar
  colour palette of fabrics, rather than those that match exactly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.128190Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-parts-plate-print
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that all parts of the plate will print."@en ;
  curric:correction """Show and remind pupils that only the raised parts of the plate will print,
  and the carved parts will stay blank."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.129596Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-sculpture-built-stay-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Once a sculpture is built, it should always stay the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some sculptures are meant to change over time. Artists might add to them,
  reuse parts or let nature affect them. Change can tell new stories and show that art is
  alive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.129647Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-two-pieces-clay-pressed-together
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Two pieces of clay can just be pressed together to attach them."@en ;
  curric:correction """Clay needs to be scored and slip applied to create a strong bond, just like
  glue helps stick paper together."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.131015Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-realise-robots-used-real
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some children might not realise that robots are used in real life, such as in
  hospitals, factories, and homes."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that robots do appear in films and books, but they are also
  used in real life. For example, robots help doctors in hospitals, build cars in factories,
  and even explore space for NASA."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.131872Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-sculptures-made-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think sculptures can only be made from one material, like clay or
  metal, rather than a combination of assembled materials."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show images of sculptures made from various materials (e.g. cardboard, wood,
  metal, plastic). Discuss with the class how combining materials can make sculptures more
  interesting or practical."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.132368Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-design-thinking-artists-people-good
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Design thinking is only for artists or people who are good at drawing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Design thinking is for everyone - it's more about problem-solving than
  creating beautiful artworks. Sketches help communicate ideas, and they don’t have to be
  visually striking to be effective."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.132974Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-street-art-vandalism-illegal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All street art is vandalism and illegal."@en ;
  curric:correction """While some graffiti is done without permission, many street artists get
  permission or are commissioned to create their work. Street art can be a respected and
  impactful form of expression."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.137198Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-materials-simple-art
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some materials are too simple to be art."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupls that artists like El Anatsui use simple, reused materials to
  make powerful work about memory, movement and transformation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.137310Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-tone-making-things
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may believe that tone is only about making things darker and that
  shading should be done with harsh, straight lines."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Tone includes both light and dark areas, and the goal is to show the full
  range of tones, from light highlights to deep shadows. Using the side of the pencil for
  softer shading, helps to avoid harsh lines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.138129Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-work-sketchbooks-purchased-shop
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists can only work in sketchbooks purchased from a shop."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists can work in lots of different styles of
  sketchbook, including ones they have made themselves."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.138615Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-beads-decoration
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Beads are just for decoration."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that beads can tell stories, show who someone is, or carry
  messages. In many cultures around the world, beads are worn to remember, to celebrate, or
  to show strength. The patterns and shapes often have deep meanings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.139254Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-makeup-used-cover-imperfections-cannot
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Makeup is only used to cover imperfections and cannot be used to tell a story,
  represent a theme or have fun with one's appearance."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that makeup is much more than decoration. It is a powerful
  way to express identity, emotions and celebration, and it helps bring people together in
  shared joy and creativity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.139889Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-patterns-need-grid
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that patterns do not need a grid to be structured."@en ;
  curric:correction "While freehand patterns exist, grids help maintain consistency."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.140498Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-mixing-lots-colours
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that mixing in lots of colours makes a better brown."@en ;
  curric:correction """Overmixing paint can lead to a muddy, unappealing colour, rather than a
  clean, rich brown."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.140503Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-papers-same-texture
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All papers have the same texture."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that different papers have different textures. For example,
  tracing paper is smooth and thin, while watercolor paper is thick and textured. Materials
  can look and behave differently depending on the surface of the paper."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.140539Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-shadows-black
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that shadows are always black."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage pupils to cast shadows and to look at the tone of the shadow.
  Observe the tone on different coloured objects. Draw pupils' attention to the fact that
  shadows are not always black."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.142115Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-maquette-final-sculpture
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think a maquette is the final sculpture and needs to be large. They
  may also jump into adding small details before constructing the basic form."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that a maquette is a smaller version to plan and test ideas
  before making a bigger sculpture. The main shape and structure need to be built first to
  support the details."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.142301Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-artists-need-directly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that artists need to have directly experienced something or
  physically visited somewhere to be inspired to create an artwork."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that artists can be inspired by the rainforest without being
  physically present there. Clarify that art inspired by rainforests could focus on plants,
  landscapes, or abstract interpretations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.144120Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-right-wrong-way-rearrange-lines
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There is a right and wrong way in which to rearrange lines and shapes when
  making abstract art."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There is no right or wrong - in abstract art shapes and lines can be
  rearranged according to the intentions of the artist."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.147140Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cutting-complex-shapes-move-scissors
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "When cutting complex shapes, we move the scissors rather than the paper."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils to move the paper, rather than the scissors when cutting, with
  their thumbs facing upwards towards the ceiling."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.147352Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-objects-art-decoration
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Objects in art are just for decoration."@en ;
  curric:correction """Objects often have meanings. For example, a crown might mean power. When
  planning, think carefully about what each object could represent in your story artwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.147638Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-masks-used-disguise
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All masks are used for disguise."@en ;
  curric:correction "Masks can also be used for cultural ceremonies, art and storytelling."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.149349Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-monsters-myths-films-portrayed-evil
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Monsters in myths and films are always portrayed as evil."@en ;
  curric:correction """Monsters in myths and films are not always portrayed as evil. Creating
  monsters can involve using different features that portray a friendly or approachable
  character."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.149935Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-nature-patterns-perfectly-repeated
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "In nature, patterns are perfectly repeated."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that in nature, patterns sometimes repeat but the shapes,
  colours or lines are slightly different."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150291Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-urban-landscapes-cannot-contain-natural
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Urban landscapes cannot contain any natural features."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that both natural and urban landscapes can have a mix of
  natural and human-made features, but natural landscapes focus more on nature, and urban
  landscapes focus more on buildings and roads."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150979Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-intricate-designs-necessary
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that intricate designs are necessary, however simple shapes
  with clear details often work best for creating patterns."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage pupils to sketch a few different simple shapes and test how they
  repeat in a pattern. You can also cut out your motif and arrange multiple copies to see
  how they fit together."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.151644Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-monoprinting-means-making
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that monoprinting means making multiple copies of the same
  image."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Through discussion and observation, remind pupils that each print is slightly
  different because of the way ink is applied and removed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.152368Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-largest-features-facial-expression-convey
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The largest features of a facial expression convey the most emotion."@en ;
  curric:correction """Applying details and small adjustments to a facial expression such as tone,
  texture and highlights can make them more dynamic, expressive and realistic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.158787Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-reviewing-work-completing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that reviewing work after completing is not necessary."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that reviewing your work after finishing it is very important.
  It helps you spot any small mistakes, like jumps in the animation or unclear movements,
  which can make a big difference in how smooth and professional the animation looks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162805Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-calligraphy-decorative-handwriting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Calligraphy is just decorative handwriting."@en ;
  curric:correction """Calligraphy is an art form with specific techniques, not just decorative
  handwriting."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165269Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-characters-important-part
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might believe that the characters are the only important part of the
  animation and that scenery doesn't matter. They also may believe that scenery is only for
  decorative purposes."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Addressing these misconceptions through discussion and reference to examples
  can help students understand the importance of scenery in clay animation and how it
  enhances storytelling."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165896Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-kaleidoscope-patterns-circular
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All kaleidoscope patterns are circular."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that while many have a circular appearance, kaleidoscope
  patterns can also be based on squares, triangles, and other geometric grids."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.166117Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-chine-coll-gluing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that Chine collé is just gluing paper onto a print after it
  is finished."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that the thin paper is applied before printing, so it bonds as part
  of the printmaking process."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.168451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-shadow-appears-around-object-single
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Shadow appears all around the object in a single, dark tone. Pupils may also
  draw shadows as a solid, dark shape."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask pupils to draw an arrow to show where the light is coming from. Remind
  pupils to look carefully at their object and consider where the shadow is darkest and
  where the shadow fades."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.169155Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-patterns-art-symmetrical-repetitive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Patterns in art are always symmetrical and repetitive."@en ;
  curric:correction """While many patterns do follow symmetrical or repetitive structures, patterns
  in art can also be organic, irregular, and asymmetrical."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.169901Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-repeat-pattern-means
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that a repeat pattern means just stamping the same image
  randomly."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Demonstrate how patterns can follow a structured repetition, showing examples
  of tiling techniques."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.169907Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-insect-needs-centre
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think the insect needs to be in the centre of the page for a
  balanced composition."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that composition can be balanced even if the insect is placed
  off-centre. Balance is about how all elements (insect, plants, background) work together,
  not just where the main subject is."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170467Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-adding-detail-make
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that adding more detail will always make a print better."@en ;
  curric:correction """While detail can be important in some art, too many tiny or delicate details
  can get lost or not transfer properly when printing. It’s actually more effective to use
  bold, simple shapes and lines to create a clear and striking print."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170989Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-texture-something-feels
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that texture is only about how something feels when
  touched."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that in art, texture can also be shown visually, like drawing
  rough bark or smooth leaves, even if you can’t physically feel it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.171130Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
